TY  - JOUR
AU  - Ellison, Glenn
AU  - Fudenberg, Drew
T1  - Knife-Edge or Plateau: When Do Market Models Tip?*
PY  - 2003
Y1  - 2003/11/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355303322552793
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 118
IS  - 4
SP  - 1249
EP  - 1278
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper studies whether agents must agglomerate at a single location in a class of models of two-sided interaction. In these models there is an increasing returns effect that favors agglomeration, but also a crowding or market-impact effect that makes agents prefer to be in a market with fewer agents of their own type. We show that such models do not tip in the way the term is commonly used. Instead, they have a broad plateau of equilibria with two active markets, and tipping occurs only when one market is below a critical size threshold. Our assumptions are fairly weak, and are satisfied in Krugman's model of labor market pooling, a heterogeneous-agent version of Pagano's asset market model, and Ellison, Fudenberg, and Möbius' model of competing auctions.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355303322552793
ER  - 



